Wash and dry produce. Halve, peel, and finely dice @yellow onion{1} until you have ¾ cup
(1 1/2 cups for 4 servings). Drain @black beans{1} over a small #bowl{}, reserving liquid.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a large #pot{} over medium-high heat. Add onion; cook,
stirring, until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add @Southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}; cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in @Tex-Mex paste{1}; cook until slightly darkened in color, ~{1%minute}.

> Once the onion is softened, add beef or organic beef to pot; season with salt and pepper and
> cook, stirring frequently, until browned and cooked through, 4-6 minutes. Cook through the rest
> of the step as instructed.

Add @ground beef{10%oz} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}; cook, stirring frequently,
until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir @mushroom stock concentrate{2}, beans, half the @crushed tomatoes{1%14oz can}, 1 cup water,
and ¼ cup reserved bean liquid into pot. (For 4 servings, use all the crushed tomatoes,
2 cups water, and ½ cup bean liquid.) Bring to a boil and cook, stirring occasionally, until
thickened, ~{5-8%minutes}.

> TIP: Prefer your broth a bit thicker? Simmer a little longer—or simmer a little less if you
> prefer a thinner broth! You're the chef, after all.

Taste and season with salt and pepper. Turn off heat.

Crush a few @blue corn tortilla chips{1.5%oz}.

Divide soup between #bowls{} and top with @white cheddar cheese{½%cup}, @smoky red pepper crema{2%tbsp}, and as many crushed tortilla chips as you like. Serve with whole tortilla chips on the side.

> TIP: Start with a few crushed chips and add more as you go to keep them crunchy!

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.